04086nam a22006375i 9781477305492DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773054927 a10.7560/3024912doi  a(DE-B1597)588703  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a985 .022231 aNair, Stella, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAt Home with the Sapa Inca :bArchitecture, Space, and Legacy at Chinchero /cStella Nair. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tOn Quechua Orthography -- tIntroduction -- t1 Pirca - Wall -- t2 Pacha - Place and Time -- t3 Pampa - Plaza -- t4 Puncu - Doorway -- t5 Uasi - House -- t6 Pata - Platform -- t7 Llacta - Community -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy examining the stunning stone buildings and dynamic spaces of the royal estate of Chinchero, Nair brings to light the rich complexity of Inca architecture. This investigation ranges from the paradigms of Inca scholarship and a summary of Inca cultural practices to the key events of Topa Inca’s reign and the many individual elements of Chinchero’s extraordinary built environment. What emerges are the subtle, often sophisticated ways in which the Inca manipulated space and architecture in order to impose their authority, identity, and agenda. The remains of grand buildings, as well as a series of deft architectural gestures in the landscape, reveal the unique places that were created within the royal estate and how one space deeply informed the other. These dynamic settings created private places for an aging ruler to spend time with a preferred wife and son, while also providing impressive spaces for imperial theatrics that reiterated the power of Topa Inca, the choice of his preferred heir, and the ruler’s close relationship with sacred forces. This careful study of architectural details also exposes several false paradigms that have profoundly misguided how we understand Inca architecture, including the belief that it ended with the arrival of Spaniards in the Andes. Instead, Nair reveals how, amidst the entanglement and violence of the European encounter, an indigenous town emerged that was rooted in Inca ways of understanding space, place, and architecture and that paid homage to a landscape that defined home for Topa Inca.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aArchitecture and anthropologyzPeruzChinchero (District). 0aExcavations (Archaeology)xInterpretive programszPeruzChinchero (District). 0aInca architecture. 0aIncasxHistory. 0aSocial archaeologyzPeruzChinchero (District). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477305492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477305492/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK